{
  "doc_id": "12577",
  "text": "MRI can discriminate between healthy and dystrophic muscles of mice in vivo and chronologically follow the extent of tissue damage and repair, qualitatively in images [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and quantitatively with MR spectroscopy. [CITATION_3] Albumin-targeted MRI contrast agents, such as gadolinium, have been used to quantitatively study the permeability of myofibers in different models of dystrophy [CITATION_4] and to improve the imaging resolution. [CITATION_5] MRI has also been used in studies of the dystrophic dog model for preclinical assessment of therapeutic interventions. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] The ability to conduct in vivo 3D tissue analysis of an individual animal over time is attractive. The performance of high-resolution systems (∼30 to 40 μm) [CITATION_8] is approaching that required to image individual myofibers, but access, cost, and the long acquisition times of MRI remain challenges impeding the uptake of this imaging modality for studies of mouse models of DMD.",
